    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-02-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-02-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="73"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d73">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72116/532</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-02-21">
                            <hi rend="italic">21 February, 1918</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: I must say I am afraid of <hi
                        rend="underline">any</hi> expression of policy framed jointly at Paris.
                    There has been none yet that seemed to me even touched with wisdom. I see that
                    you have sought to suggest and safeguard, but I am afraid that statesmen like
                    our friend L—G. will not care to be guided and will rather rejoice in a somewhat
                    crude and cynical rejoinder to the Red Cross.</p>
                <p>I approve the despatch to Sharp, however, and am quite willing to subscribe to a
                    proper reply if they will let us see it beforehand. Sharp can cable it, and the
                    delay will not be serious.</p>
                <p>Faithfully Yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>W. W.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
